Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Peel and grate the 
@garlic cloves{2}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the 
@lentils{1%cup} in a #sieve{}. Chop the @lemon{1/2} in half.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #small saucepan{} on medium heat. When hot, 
add the shallot and cook, stirring, until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the 
garlic and cook for another ~{30%seconds}. Stir the lentils through the shallot 
and garlic until piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat.

Off the heat, stir the @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and @wholegrain mustard{1%tsp} 
into the lentils along with the @olive oil{2%tbsp} a pinch of @salt{} and 
@pepper{}. Set aside.

Roughly chop the @dill{1%bunch}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Roughly chop 
the @walnuts{20}(chopped). Chop the @cooked beetroot{250%g} into 6 segments.

> TIP: Wear gloves when handling the beetroot to avoid staining your hands!

== Salad ==

In a #large bowl{}, stir together the @honey{15%ml}, lemon juice and 
@olive oil{2%tbsp} along with a pinch of salt and pepper. Add the 
@baby leaf mix{50%g} and half the walnuts and toss to coat.

Gently toss half the dill through the lentils. Arrange the baby leaf salad on 
your plates and top with the lentils. Place the beetroot on top and crumble 
over the @goat's cheese{125%g}. Finish with the remaining walnuts and dill. 
Enjoy!